
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `expiry` baraye tayeen ya tagheer tarikh enghezaaye password baraye karbar ha estefade mishavad. Yani, ba in dastoor mitavanid mohlat password-haye karbar-ha ra moratab konid ta amniat behtar shavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `expiry username` --> 👤 Namayesh tarikh enghezaaye password baraye username-e moshakhas.
    🔹 `expiry -d days username` --> 📅 Tayeen tarikh enghezaaye password baraye username bar asase tedad rooz.
    🔹 `expiry -m months username` --> 🗓️ Tayeen tarikh enghezaaye password baraye username bar asase tedad mah.
    🔹 `expiry -never username` --> ♾️ Password hich vaght expire nemishavad (tavsiye nemishavad).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ expiry john

    🔹 Namayesh tarikh enghezaaye password baraye karbar john.

    $ sudo expiry -d 90 jane

    🔹 Tarikh enghezaaye password karbar jane ra 90 rooz digar tayeen mikonad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ expiry root

    🔹 Pasokh shamel tarikh va etela'at digar dar morede enghezaye password karbar root ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `expiry` command is used to set or modify the password expiration date for user accounts. This allows you to enforce password policies and improve security.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `expiry username` --> 👤 Display the password expiration date for the specified username.
    🔹 `expiry -d days username` --> 📅 Set the password expiration date for the username based on the number of days.
    🔹 `expiry -m months username` --> 🗓️ Set the password expiration date for the username based on the number of months.
    🔹 `expiry -never username` --> ♾️ The password will never expire (not recommended).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ expiry john

    🔹 Display the password expiration date for the user john.

    $ sudo expiry -d 90 jane

    🔹 Sets the password expiration date for the user jane to 90 days from now.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ expiry root

    🔹 The output will include the date and other information regarding the password expiration for the root user.
